We  talked last month about a shareholder proposal at Fox Corp. The proposa=
l essentially asked Fox to prioritize journalistic integrity over profits a=
t Fox News, specifically by becoming a public benefit corporation focused o=
n the public benefit of accurately informing its viewers. This feels like i=
t is not going to happen for a lot of reasons, one of them being that Ruper=
t Murdoch owns 41% of the voting power of Fox stock, though that is not the=
 only reason.[2]But what I like about this proposal is its argument for=C2=
=A0why=C2=A0shareholders should vote for it. The argument is not =E2=80=9Cp=
rioritizing truth over money will make more money for shareholders in the l=
ong run=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is absolutely an argument that one co=
uld make, and which is structurally similar to  a lot of arguments for othe=
r environmental, social and governance-y ideas. (=E2=80=9CSure this oil com=
pany will make less money if it shifts to clean energy than if it pumps=C2=
=A0as=C2=A0much oil as possible, but in the long run its value will be maxi=
mized by making the transition to clean energy early,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Csure this social-media company will make less money if it doesn=E2=80=99=
t serve up constant outrages but in the long run people will get tired of t=
he outrages and leave,=E2=80=9D etc.)=C2=A0Nor is the argument =E2=80=9Cpri=
oritizing truth over money will cost you, the shareholder, money, but you a=
re a nice person and you should care more about the world than about maximi=
zing your stock price.=E2=80=9D This again is an argument that one could ma=
ke, and it is another standard strand of ESG argumentation. That=E2=80=99s =
why people are willing to accept lower interest rates on  green bonds than =
on non-green=C2=A0bonds: They will sacrifice some economic return in exchan=
ge for doing good for the world.=C2=A0Instead, the people making the Fox sh=
areholder proposal =E2=80=94=C2=A0a group called the Shareholder Commons In=
c. =E2=80=94=C2=A0argue that it is in the=C2=A0financial=C2=A0interests of =
Fox shareholders,=C2=A0not=C2=A0as Fox shareholders, but as shareholders of=
=C2=A0other=C2=A0public companies. Last=C2=A0Friday the Shareholder Commons=
 filed a new statement in support of their proposal. A sample:The Sharehold=
er Commons is a non-profit organization that promotes systems-first investm=
ent that better serves diversified shareholders who invest in our economy. =
=E2=80=A6The Proposal asks the Company to account for the risk to investor =
portfolios created by the effect its journalism has on the economy.In short=
, the Proposal seeks to align the Company=E2=80=99s goals with those of its=
 diversified shareholders. =E2=80=A6Almost all of Fox=E2=80=99s shareholder=
s (other than the Murdoch family) are diversified investors who depend on a=
n economy that succeeds for everyone over the long term. If your interests =
as an investor are diversified across the economy, then Fox=E2=80=99s curre=
nt business model threatens your long-term returns by delivering false and =
harmful information to a credulous audience. The Proposal addresses this pr=
oblem by altering the Company=E2=80=99s legal purpose.As a PBC, Fox will be=
 able to account directly for the long-term risks to the systems and instit=
utions critical to a well-functioning economy. This new flexibility will al=
low Fox to protect your portfolio by limiting misinformation that undermine=
s the healthy systems necessary for a successful economy. As long as Fox re=
mains a conventional corporation, this is highly unlikely to happen, becaus=
e lawyers will caution directors that prioritizing journalistic integrity o=
r systemic concerns over financial returns is a breach of their fiduciary d=
uties that may subject them to liability. As a leading Delaware law firm re=
cently explained, =E2=80=9CIf the interests of the stockholders and the oth=
er constituencies conflict=E2=80=A6 the board=E2=80=99s fiduciary duties re=
quire it to act in a manner that furthers the interests of the stockholders=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The courts narrowly interpret such shareholder interests as=
 including only the financial return they receive from the corporation, irr=
espective of whether such returns impose greater costs on the rest of their=
 portfolios.This legally mandated focus on individual company returns is ha=
rmful to your portfolio as a diversified investor. As we discuss in detail =
below, Fox is maximizing its revenues and profits through a business strate=
gy that externalizes costs that the rest of a diversified portfolio sustain=
s. This is a bad deal for you.Among the specific claims they make are =E2=
=80=9CFox is a major source of climate denialism=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chigh=
er local viewership of Fox News Channel is associated with lower vaccinatio=
n rates.=E2=80=9D I mention these examples because around here we often tal=
k about the theory that common ownership of big corporations might  solve c=
oordination problems and force (or allow) companies to  internalize externa=
lities. And those are the two examples we most often discuss. As in: Climat=
e change will be bad for lots of companies, oil companies do not internaliz=
e the carbon costs of their production, oil-company=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0=
own lots of companies and bear those costs, therefore oil-company sharehold=
ers will force oil companies to reduce carbon emissions. Or  as in: Covid-1=
9 vaccination will be good for lots of companies (economy reopening, etc.),=
 pharmaceutical companies do not necessarily internalize all of the social =
gains of widespread vaccination, pharma-company=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0own =
lots of companies and benefit from those social gains, therefore pharma-com=
pany shareholders will force pharma companies to make Covid-19 vaccines and=
 distribute them cheaply.=C2=A0Fox is neither an oil company nor a pharmace=
utical company but every little bit helps I guess?=C2=A0What is new here is=
 the explicit, coordinated appeal to common shareholders to use their votin=
g power in one company for the benefit of their other companies. The main t=
hing that I want to say is that this is=C2=A0interesting, and=C2=A0logical.=
 Public companies are largely owned by large diversified institutional shar=
eholders (though not so much Fox), and it does make sense for them to act i=
n a way that is good for their overall financial interests rather than for =
each individual company to try to maximize its own price at the expense of =
the others. Why shouldn=E2=80=99t modern corporate governance work for the =
actual shareholders, rather than for an old-timey conception of what a comp=
any is?But the other thing that I want to say is that this is=C2=A0risky? T=
he big diversified shareholders might go around saying things like =E2=80=
=9Cwe are long-term investors in the global economy so we care about sustai=
nability and the rule of law and other good societal-level stuff,=E2=80=9D =
but they mostly=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0go around saying =E2=80=9Cwe own al=
l the companies so we care more about growing the overall pie than about an=
y one company=E2=80=99s share of it.=E2=80=9D Those things are related, but=
 not quite the same.If 60% of a company is owned by diversified institution=
al investors, and they vote for a proposal that would reduce the company=E2=
=80=99s profits but increase the profits of=C2=A0other=C2=A0public companie=
s, would the concentrated shareholders who own the other 40% have cause to =
sue them? =E2=80=9CYou control the company, you have some duty to the minor=
ity shareholders, and you betrayed us to increase the value of your other h=
oldings.=E2=80=9D That does not seem like a trivial argument?For instance, =
if a big public company offers to buy a little public company, it might off=
er a relatively low cash premium, because why spend cash? The target compan=
y might say =E2=80=9Cno, we want a bigger premium=C2=A0for our shareholders=
.=E2=80=9D But enough of the target company=E2=80=99s shareholders might al=
so be shareholders of the acquirer to approve the deal anyway: =E2=80=9CThe=
 premium=C2=A0is just money going from one pocket to another, why incur fin=
ancing costs?=E2=80=9D[3] You could even imagine the acquirer=C2=A0saying t=
hat, to the target shareholders: =E2=80=9CLook, you are all our shareholder=
s too, why make us pay a premium for your shares that will ultimately come =
out of your pockets?=E2=80=9D The minority of the target-company shareholde=
rs whose entire investment is in that one company might feel aggrieved. =E2=
=80=9CWe bought this stock expecting the company to maximize its value, but=
 it turns out it maximized something else.=E2=80=9DTesla Inc. shareholders =
have been suing Elon Musk, Tesla=E2=80=99s Technoking and biggest sharehold=
er,=C2=A0alleging that he cut a bad deal for Tesla to buy SolarCity because=
 he was also a big SolarCity shareholder and would benefit from the deal on=
 that side. The big diversified institutional investors are not in quite th=
e same position, but there are some parallels.This is presumably why the Fo=
x proposal calls for it to become a public benefit corporation: If a regula=
r public company, with fiduciary obligations to its shareholders, explicitl=
y prioritized the interests of its large diversified shareholders over thos=
e of its smaller concentrated shareholders, those concentrated shareholders=
 might sue, and they=E2=80=99d have an interesting case.Also we have talked=
 a lot about one particular sort of coordination problem that common owners=
hip might solve, one particular way that companies might increase the value=
 of=C2=A0other=C2=A0companies by sacrificing some of their own value. That =
is=C2=A0reducing competition:=C2=A0If two competing companies have common o=
wners, then Company A might say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll sell to customers in =
the West and keep prices high=E2=80=9D and Company B might say =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99ll sell to companies in the East and keep prices high.=E2=80=9D If=
 they were fully independent they might each plot to invade each other's ma=
rkets, cut prices and take market share, but if they=E2=80=99re maximizing =
the common good =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they have common shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0they won=E2=80=99t.This is a popular theory that a lot of people f=
ind very implausible, in part because big index funds almost never go aroun=
d saying things like =E2=80=9Cwe want each of our companies to sacrifice th=
eir own profitability for the good of the overall portfolio.=E2=80=9D But i=
t does feel like explicit appeals to that theory are becoming a bit more co=
mmon.
