ctor over the past five years; the returns are volatile and investors feel =
ESG pressures,=E2=80=9D says Wil VanLoh, who runs Quantum Energy Partners, =
which manages $18 billion, making it one of the few remaining big energy pr=
ivate-equity funds. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s been a huge retreat in availab=
le capital.=E2=80=9DIf your basic theory of ESG investing is =E2=80=9Cwe wi=
ll brand our products as ESG in order to attract customers,=E2=80=9D  that =
also seems to be working:BlackRock Inc.=E2=80=99s push into sustainable inv=
esting is producing big results.Of the $98 billion in long-term net flows t=
hat the firm took in last quarter, about one third, or $32 billion, went in=
to sustainable funds -- a quarterly record. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CBlackRock=E2=
=80=99s strong commitment to ESG in recent years gives the firm a firm move=
r advantage to capitalize on this high-growth opportunity,=E2=80=9D Kyle Sa=
nders, an analyst at Edward Jones, said in a note Wednesday.Really=C2=A0any=
=C2=A0theory of ESG investing has to include a claim like =E2=80=9Cpublic c=
ompanies will do more ESG things if their investors demand it.=E2=80=9D But=
 the investors are mostly intermediaries themselves; big institutional shar=
eholders own stock on behalf of their customers, and the same basic dynamic=
 applies: =E2=80=9CBig institutional investors will do more ESG things if=
=C2=A0their=C2=A0customers want it.=E2=80=9D It seems like they do.Meanwhil=
e here=E2=80=99s a story about greenium:Investors have long been willing to=
 pay a premium for green bonds, rewarding companies or governments that wan=
t to clean up their act by giving them lower borrowing costs.But, amid a bo=
om in the issuance of bonds whose proceeds are earmarked for environmental =
spending, there are signs that this so-called =E2=80=9Cgreenium=E2=80=9D is=
 being eroded. =E2=80=A6Many investors are beginning to question the logic =
of paying extra for a bond with a =E2=80=9Cgreen=E2=80=9D label, arguing th=
at there are better ways to incentivise sovereign or corporate borrowers to=
 boost their spending on environmentally friendly projects.These fund manag=
ers say that companies or governments should be rewarded =E2=80=94 or penal=
ised =E2=80=94 based on their green efforts as a whole, rather than hiving =
off a small part of their activities and rebadging the debt used to pay for=
 it.=E2=80=9CWe always evaluate an issuer in its entirety, not just one bon=
d,=E2=80=9D says Madeleine King, co-head of global credit research at Legal=
 & General Investment Management. She argues that it makes little sense to =
pay a premium for a green bond compared with a normal bond from the same co=
mpany when the creditworthiness =E2=80=94 and the sustainability credential=
s =E2=80=94 of the issuer are the same in either case.This seems like a sto=
ry about the maturation of ESG investing. In the olden days, a company coul=
d sell regular bonds to regular investors and green bonds to ESG investors;=
 =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll do some environmental stuff with the money you give=
 us=E2=80=9D was a good enough incentive to get the ESG investors to give t=
he company cheap money. ESG investing was a small niche and you could micro=
-target it. But now ESG is important enough to enough investors and compani=
es that the ESG investors can just buy regular bonds from companies that me=
et their ESG criteria and avoid buying any bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0regular or =
green =E2=80=94=C2=A0from companies that don=E2=80=99t. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=
=99ll sell regular bonds to fund our pollution and green bonds to clean it =
up=E2=80=9D is not as attractive a model as =E2=80=9Cwe won=E2=80=99t pollu=
te, and here are some bonds.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Finally, if your view of ESG inv=
esting is that it should be illegal for investment managers to prioritize a=
