10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Methane</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way business works is that you hav=
e some assets and they=E2=80=99re funded by some liabilities. The assets ge=
nerate some income which you use to pay back the liabilities.=C2=A0You borr=
ow some money, you buy a machine for your factory, the machine makes widget=
s, you sell the widgets, you get money, you pay back the money you borrowed=
, you have some money left over as profit, life is good. One way to make mo=
re profit is to make the assets worth more, to make them produce more incom=
e; if you can tune up the widget machine to make more widgets then you will=
 have more profit.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another way to make more=
 profit is to make the liabilities worth less. This is the weirder way. If =
you borrow $100 to buy a widget machine, and the widget machine produces $1=
20 of widgets, then you have $20 of profit. If you go to your lenders and s=
ay =E2=80=9Cinstead of $100 what if I paid you back $75?=E2=80=9D and they =
say =E2=80=9Csure that's fine no problem=E2=80=9D then you have $45=C2=A0of=
 profit. You got an extra $25 of profit from not having to pay off all your=
 debt. Why would that work? It doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>generally=C2=A0</em=
>work. But sometimes it could.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A while back=
, people <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25340495.=
257884/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNTQxNGMyNTQtMGRlZi0xMWUxLTlkNDAt=
MDAxNDRmZWFiZGMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5a72bb57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sometimes</a> g=
ot <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25340495.257884=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNDIxMWY5MzItZmJkNC0xMWUwLTkyODMtMDAxND=
RmZWFiNDlh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB52929859" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">worked up</a> about h=
ow banks were accounting for the changes in fair value of their own debt. B=
asically if a bank issued a $100 bond for $100, and then its credit got wor=
se and the bond only traded at $95, the bank would say =E2=80=9Cwell we sol=
d something worth $95 for $100 so I guess we have $5 in income=E2=80=9D and=
 add=C2=A0$5 to its net income. The result was that when banks had a really=
=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>quarter =E2=80=94=C2=A0when investors started worry=
ing that they were riskier and might fail =E2=80=94 their credit spreads in=
creased and they reported billions of dollars of=C2=A0<em>gains=C2=A0</em>d=
ue to changes in the value of their debt. (Conversely, when things got=C2=
=A0better, they reported big=C2=A0<em>losses</em>.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">This feels wrong. Your own credit getting worse doesn=E2=80=
=99t get you=C2=A0<em>more money</em>. People got=C2=A0mad about this, abou=
t how the accounting failed to match the=C2=A0reality of the cash flows; ev=
entually <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25340495.=
257884/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTItMDctMTAv=
YmFua3MtbWF5LXNlZS1kdmEtY2hhbmdlcy1hcy1nYWlucy1wcmVkaWN0ZWQtZm9yLXNlY29uZC1=
xdWFydGVy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBca645712" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the accounting was ch=
anged</a>. But if you=E2=80=99re a financial engineer this is nothing to ge=
t mad about. If you=E2=80=99re a financial engineer this is an inspiration.=
 =E2=80=9CHow can we turn our own credit getting worse into=C2=A0<em>cash</=
em>,=E2=80=9D is the correct question to ask.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Here is one=C2=A0way. You borrow $100 to buy an asset worth $100. You us=
e it for a while, it makes widgets that you sell for a profit. It depreciat=
es,=C2=A0it gets old, it produces fewer widgets. Now it=E2=80=99s worth $50=
. You still owe $100 on the loan. The asset plus the loan are worth negativ=
e $50. If you sell them together =E2=80=94=C2=A0the asset and the loan =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a buyer should be willing to pay you negative $50 for them. Tha=
t is, you=E2=80=99d have to pay the buyer to take on the asset plus the loa=
n.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if you find a buyer with =
terrible, terrible credit? The buyer will say =E2=80=9CI can buy this asset=
 and it will generate $50 of profits for me, which I will spend. Then I wil=
l have to pay off this $100 loan, but =E2=80=94=C2=A0and here's the trick =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0I won=E2=80=99t do that.=E2=80=9D Eventually the lender will=
 sue the buyer for the money, the buyer will turn their pockets inside out =
and gesture comically to their lack of money, and the lender will get, you =
know, nothing.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much will that buyer =
pay you for the asset plus the liability? I dunno, probably not $50, but mo=
re than negative $50. Maybe they=E2=80=99ll pay you $5 for it, which is $55=
 more than it=E2=80=99s worth to you.=C2=A0Maybe they=E2=80=99ll value the =
package at $25 (or $50?) on their books, reporting an immediate gain of $20=
. Everybody wins! Except, to be clear, the lender. The lender loses $100.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lenders do not like this sort of thi=
ng and they=C2=A0try to avoid it; you probably cannot do this trade with yo=
ur actual widget-making machine. But there are other sorts of liabilities.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s one. The way a natural gas w=
ell works is that you drill a well, and then you pump gas out of it for a w=
hile, and then it runs out of gas, and then you have to =E2=80=9Ccap=E2=80=
=9D the well, fill it in with concrete so it doesn=E2=80=99t just leak meth=
ane into the atmosphere forever. In the U.S., state laws impose=C2=A0this c=
apping requirement on the owner of the well; it is a sort of liability that=
 comes with the well. If you drill a successful well, you get an asset (a h=
ole in the ground that produces natural gas that you can sell for money) an=
d a liability (the obligation to spend money in the future to fill the hole=
 with concrete). Early in the well=E2=80=99s life, the asset is worth a lot=
 (it produces a lot of gas) and the liability is worth a little (you will n=
ot have to fill it in for many years, so the net present value of the money=
 you will eventually spend to fill it in is low). You open the well and you=
 have a $100 asset and a $5 liability. Good work.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">But then you pump for a while and you deplete most of the gas =
and now the asset is only worth $10 because it won=E2=80=99t produce much m=
ore gas. And you know that in a year or two you=E2=80=99ll have to pay $20 =
to cap it, so you record that liability at a present value of, you know, $1=
8 or whatever.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then someone comes=
 to you and says: Look, this well will produce $10 more of gas, and I can s=
ell that gas and make a profit and spend it. And I can do this much=C2=A0<e=
m>slower=C2=A0</em>than you: You will just pump the rest of the gas out and=
 have to cap the well in a year or two, but me, I=E2=80=99m in no rush. I w=
ill drag out the process so that I can produce a little gas for like 20 yea=
rs. Then in 20 years regulators will say =E2=80=9Cokay time to cap the well=
=E2=80=9D and I will turn my pockets inside out and gesture comically to my=
 lack of money. Maybe I=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cjust give me 20 more y=
ears,=E2=80=9D and the regulators will say okay, because what=E2=80=99s the=
 alternative?=C2=A0And then in 40 years, who knows, maybe I=E2=80=99ll cap =
the well, but I=E2=80=99ll definitely have spent all the money by then.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much is that well worth to that buy=
er? I dunno? Maybe $7? They get $10 worth of gas and have $3 of hassle and =
expense in deferring the capping liability indefinitely?=C2=A0If they buy i=
t from you for $2, you make a profit =E2=80=94=C2=A0you had the thing value=
d at negative $8 ($10 asset, $18 capping liability), and now you have sold =
it for positive $2 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they make a profit (since they paid $=
2 for a stream of profits worth $7). Everybody wins! Except, you know, the =
well never gets capped and methane leaks into the atmosphere forever.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is apparently a=C2=A0<em>standard=C2=A0</em=
>business model in the natural gas industry. Big well-capitalized companies=
 drill and operate productive wells, but as the wells get depleted, they ar=
e sold to small poorly capitalized companies to get the capping liabilities=
 off the big companies=E2=80=99 books. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25340495.257884/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy9kaXZlcnNpZmllZC1lbmVyZ3ktbmF0dXJhbC1nYXMtd2VsbHMtbWV0aGFuZ=
S1sZWFrcy0yMDIxLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6df3eaa9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a fascinating=
 story of financial engineering</a>=C2=A0from Bloomberg's Zachary Mider and=
 Rachel Adams-Heard:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">American o=
il executives talk about a food chain in their industry. Big, well-capitali=
zed companies tend to be the ones to drill wells and harvest the first year=
s=E2=80=99 production. As output tapers, wells typically change hands a few=
 times, then spend their golden years with a smaller, more financially shak=
y company. If that company goes broke, there=E2=80=99s no money to plug the=
 well. In most states, previous owners aren=E2=80=99t liable. That helps ex=
plain how an industry that created some of the biggest fortunes and most va=
luable companies has also produced hundreds of thousands of orphaned wells,=
 with no owner around to clean them up. The Interstate Oil &amp; Gas Compac=
t Commission estimates the number across the U.S. may be as high as 800,000=
. In August the U.S. Senate approved an infrastructure bill that includes $=
4.7 billion to begin tackling the problem.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">In general, if you are looking to monetize something like =E2=
=80=9Cwe are going to acquire liabilities and not pay them,=E2=80=9D you do=
 have to be a=C2=A0smaller, financially shaky company. But Mider and Adams-=
Heard=E2=80=99s story is actually about a larger and more valuable company,=
 Diversified Energy Co., which is =E2=80=9Cthe largest well owner in the co=
untry=E2=80=9D with 69,000 U.S. natural gas wells, and which, uh, may or ma=
y not be pursuing this strategy at scale?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Diversified=E2=80=99s breakneck growth has alarmed some regulato=
rs, landowner groups, and industry insiders, not to mention environmental a=
dvocates. State laws require that every well be plugged with cement after i=
t runs dry, an expensive and complicated chore. At the rate Diversified is =
paying dividends to shareholders, some worry there will be nothing left whe=
n the bills come due. If a company can=E2=80=99t meet its plugging obligati=
ons, that burden falls to the state, which means Ohio, Pennsylvania, and We=
st Virginia could be stuck with a billion-dollar mess. =E2=80=9CThe model s=
eems like it=E2=80=99s built on abandoning those assets,=E2=80=9D says Ted =
Boettner, who=E2=80=99s studied abandoned wells at the Ohio River Valley In=
stitute, a regional research organization. =E2=80=9CIt looks like a liabili=
ty bomb that=E2=80=99s destined to explode.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">[Diversified founder Rusty]=C2=A0Hutson says there=E2=80=99s no c=
ause for worry. He claims to be able to squeeze more gas out of old wells t=
han other companies can and keep them going longer. On average, he figures =
his wells have an additional 50 years in them, which means there=E2=80=99s =
no hurry to start socking away money to plug them.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also means that the present value of the capp=
ing liabilities is a lot lower than it would be if the wells were going to =
be shut down tomorrow:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometime=
s the most profitable reason to extend the life of an old well isn=E2=80=99=
t the extra oil or gas that comes out. It=E2=80=99s the delay in the date w=
hen a well has to be plugged. When companies tell investors how much they e=
xpect to spend on retiring wells, they discount it by how far away that day=
 of reckoning is. On the books, a 50-year timeline makes Hutson=E2=80=99s c=
ost almost disappear.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because it plugs so m=
any wells and keeps much of the work in-house, Diversified says it can reti=
re wells for under $25,000, less than industry norms. Thanks to that, and t=
he unusually long time horizon, Diversified often records its plugging liab=
ilities at a fraction of what other companies would. In 2018 the company bo=
ught a portfolio of wells from CNX Resources Corp. CNX had pegged its clean=
up liability at $197 million. Diversified put the liability for the same we=
lls at only $14 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This may explain w=
hy Diversified frequently determines the wells it=E2=80=99s buying are wort=
h far more than what it paid=E2=80=94so much so that it books the differenc=
e as profit upfront. Since 2014 the amount Diversified has made from these =
accounting gains is more than its cumulative reported profit.=C2=A0</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, right, if you buy an asset with =
an embedded liability, and you find a way to defer the liability for <em>50=
 years</em>, that asset is worth a lot more to you than it is to the seller=
. That=E2=80=99s just good financial engineering. But this strategy is comp=
lemented by turning your pockets inside out for your creditors so they give=
 you more time to pay:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thousand=
s of wells Diversified bought were producing nothing at all, meaning they w=
ere already out of compliance. State laws require nonproductive wells to be=
 plugged promptly, so they don=E2=80=99t endanger groundwater or catch fire=
. But enforcing this law is difficult. Regulators worry that if they push c=
ompanies too hard, it can cause financial distress and reduce the chances t=
hat anything will be plugged. =E2=80=9CIf the burden is so high to plug a w=
ell, then a company may not be able to do it, and you=E2=80=99ve defeated t=
he purpose,=E2=80=9D says Eric Vendel, chief of Ohio=E2=80=99s Division of =
Oil and Gas Resources Management. That concern was especially acute for Div=
ersified, which was juggling an unprecedented number of idle wells in multi=
ple states.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, four states=E2=80=94Ke=
ntucky, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and West Virginia=E2=80=94cut deals that give D=
iversified about a decade or more to bring roughly 3,000 idle wells into co=
mpliance. If the company revives enough of those wells, it=E2=80=99s requir=
ed to plug only 20 unsalvageable ones a year in each of the four states.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Exxon Mobil Corp. owned=
 3,000 idle wells, regulators could say =E2=80=9Ccap these wells or we=E2=
=80=99ll fine you a ton of money=E2=80=9D and Exxon, which has a ton of mon=
ey, would go cap the wells. But if Diversified owns 3,000 idle wells, regul=
ators say =E2=80=9Chmm, that=E2=80=99s a lot of idle wells, better not push=
 too hard,=E2=80=9D and make them cap 80 a year. Gesturing threateningly at=
 your own creditworthiness can reduce your=C2=A0liability!</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Anyway the actual point of the article is that a lot=C2=A0o=
f these uncapped wells are spewing methane into the atmosphere and contribu=
ting to global warming,=C2=A0but I mostly wanted to talk about the financia=
l engineering. If you can offer a service like =E2=80=9Cwe will take your l=
iabilities off your hands and then defer them by 50 years,=E2=80=9D that is=
 a valuable service and you can make a nice profit from it. But it is not a=
 value-<em>creating=C2=A0</em>service. It is a value-<em>shifting=C2=A0</em=
>service. You take the value from the creditors and split it up among the b=
uyer and seller. Here the =E2=80=9Ccreditors=E2=80=9D=C2=A0are environmenta=
l regulators; ultimately the value is taken from the environment.=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a lot recently about environmen=
tal, social and governance investing through the lens of externalities. An =
important idea in ESG investing is that companies that impose costs on the =
environment or stakeholders or society will eventually be forced, by regula=
tion or social norms or whatever, to pay those costs. If you operate a prof=
itable factory that produces a ton of pollution, you will eventually have t=
o pay to clean up that pollution, and so measured correctly based on total =
costs the factory isn=E2=80=99t really profitable. The assumed mechanism fo=
r this is often future regulation: Eventually governments will wise up to c=
limate change, the theory goes, and so they will impose carbon restrictions=
 that make fossil fuels far less profitable than they are now.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is an example of=C2=A0existing regulations re=
quiring gas companies to internalize their externalities, to budget for cap=
ping their wells to avoid pollution. And it turns out that there=E2=80=99s =
a business opportunity there: If you can sell the service of re-externalizi=
ng the externalities, you can make a nice profit.</p><table class=3D"livein=
