0tcHJvZml0cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb2e49c1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a lot of arguments=
</a> for other environmental, social and governance-y ideas. (=E2=80=9CSure=
 this oil company will make less money if it shifts to clean energy than if=
 it pumps=C2=A0as=C2=A0much oil as possible, but in the long run its value =
will be maximized by making the transition to clean energy early,=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Csure this social-media company will make less money if it do=
esn=E2=80=99t serve up constant outrages but in the long run people will ge=
t tired of the outrages and leave,=E2=80=9D etc.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Nor is the argument =E2=80=9Cprioritizing truth over money wil=
l cost you, the shareholder, money, but you are a nice person and you shoul=
d care more about the world than about maximizing your stock price.=E2=80=
=9D This again is an argument that one could make, and it is another standa=
rd strand of ESG argumentation. That=E2=80=99s why people are willing to ac=
cept lower interest rates on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/25340495.257884/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
