nt in the bond market, and as his personal life becomes increasingly baroqu=
e, the letters keep getting weirder. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25340495.257884/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJuZXdzd=
2lyZS5jb20vbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9iaWxsLWdyb3NzLXJlbGVhc2VzLWludmVzdG1lbnQtb3V0=
bG9vay0teW91LW9ubHktaGFuZy10d2ljZS0zMDEzOTk0NDQuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBd595999f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">yesterday=E2=80=99s</a>. (From PR Newswire: =E2=80=
=9CLegendary bond and fixed income investor William H. (Bill) Gross today r=
eleased a new Investment Outlook, =E2=80=98You Only Hang Twice.=E2=80=99=E2=
=80=9D) Is it the weirdest monthly investor letter ever written? Quite poss=
ibly? If it qualifies as an investor letter at all?=C2=A0It leads off with =
Gross=E2=80=99s version of how he was found in contempt of court for playin=
g music too loud at night by =E2=80=9Cthe hanging judge of the Laguna Beach=
 shore, a 57-year-old lady with pierced nose stud and visible tattoos,=E2=
=80=9D and=C2=A0given a five-day suspended jail sentence, community service=
 and =E2=80=9Ca mere $1,200 fine.=E2=80=9D (This is all framed by the conce=
it that a new James Bond movie=C2=A0is being made about the affair, starrin=
g Jake Gyllenhaal as Gross; I have no idea where James Bond fits in.) Then =
it moves on to how he did his community service in a soup kitchen but was o=
ffended that the food was too good and the customers too well-dressed:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many of those requesting vegan were=
 well dressed and apparently not lacking in the finer accoutrements of dail=
y life. "We can't discriminate against those who have already been discrimi=
nated against," remarked one of the permanent staff. "We can't deny them tw=
ice". Ah yes I said to myself =E2=80=93 I know what you mean.</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then a brief pitch for=C2=A0yieldy stocks a=
s a better bet than Treasuries.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do =
think that if Gross were still employed as a bond manager and he wrote a se=
ven-paragraph investor letter that devoted two paragraphs to his brushes wi=
th the law, two paragraphs to what stocks you should buy instead of bonds, =
and three paragraphs to how soup kitchens are too cushy these days, someone=
 might have gently suggested that he tone it down? Even him, I mean? But no=
w there are no clients and no rules. I can=E2=80=99t wait for next month=E2=
=80=99s. The man has invented his own literary genre; how can you not respe=
ct that? In like five years these are going to be 20-page Knausgaardian rum=
inations ending with a single paragraph like =E2=80=9CI continue to own som=
e stocks,=E2=80=9D and they are still going to be titled =E2=80=9CInvestmen=
t Outlook.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=
